<br>
Evolutionism-<br>
<br>
Basic Theory of evolution- Over time, organisms “change” or “evolve”. The modern humans are evolved from lower life forms, those life forms evolved from even lower life forms, and those life forms were (if you go down far enough) eventually formed by the random chance combination of molecules.<br>
<br>
1) Fossil record<br>
<br>
Colin Patterson, senior paleontologist at the British Museum of Natural History, yr. unk., <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If I knew of any (evolutionary transitions), fossil or living, I would certainly have included them (In my book Evolution) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
David Raup, curator of the Field Museum of Natural History, yr unk<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> We are now 120 years after Darwin and the knowledge of the fossil record has expanded. We now have a quarter of a million fossil species, but the situation hasn’t changed much- we have even fewer examples of evolutionary transition. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So in other words, there is NO TRANSITION POINT between humans and monkeys or between ANY OTHER ORGANISM that has ever been found. But you saw some in the news early, you say? Lets address those now...<br>
<br>
Archaeopteryx- This is the so-called “transition” between birds and dinosaurs that’s been found.<br>
<br>
Hank Haangraph, The Face, 1998<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  First, fossils of the Archaeopteryx and the type of dinosaur Archaeopteryx was supposedly formed from were both found in a fine-ground German Limestone formation said to be late Jurassic. Thus, Archaeopteryx is not a likely candidate as the missing link, since birds and their alleged ancestral dinosaurs thrived during the same period of time. In addition, it should be noted that a great deal of controversy has occurred in the evolutionary community as a result of other bird fossils classified by scientists as “Late Triassic” (prior to Jurassic) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Thus… bids were found in times millions of years before Archaeopteryx fossils.<br>
<br>
2) Ape-men<br>
<br>
I’m just going to us direct quotes from Haangraph… these “fossils” are so ridiculous its almost funny.<br>
<br>
Would be if people didn’t believe it, at least.<br>
<br>
The Java man-<br>
<br>
Hank Haangraph, The Face, 1998<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  What is not so well known is that the Java man consists of nothing more than a skullcap, a femur, 3 teeth, and a great deal of imagination. Even more disturbing is the fact that the femur was found 50 feet away and a full year later. Most unsettling of all is that for almost 30 years, Duboius downplayed the discovery of 2 human skulls, which he found in close proximity to his “find” <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The Piltdown man<br>
<br>
Hank Haangraph, The Face, 1998<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> While the Pithecanthropus erectus (Java man) can best be placed in the category of fiction, Piltdown man (Eoanthropus dawsoni) may be factually described as a fraud. While the fraud may have been cleverly concieved, it was crudely carried out. The jaw of an ape was stained to make it appear as though it matched a human skull; the piltdown fossils along with accompanying bones were not only stained but reshaped. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Marvin Lubenow:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The file marks on the orangutan teeth of the lower jaw were clearly visible. The molars were misaligned and filed at two different angles. The canine tooth had been filed at two different angles. The canine tooth had been filed so far down that the pulp cavity had been exposed and plugged. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Now onto the possibilities of humanity evolving from a single-celled organism (indirectly).<br>
<br>
CHARLES DARWIN, THE ORIGIN OF SPECIES, 18??<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> To suppose an eye, with all its inimitable contrivances for adjusting the focus to different distances, for admitting different amounts of light, and for the correction of a spherical and chromatic aberration, could have been formed by natural selection, seems, I freely confess, absurd in the highest degree <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Biochemist Michael Behe, yr. unk.,<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Each of the anatomical structures Darwin thought were so simple actually involves staggeringly complicated biochemical processes <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Finally, I think this statistical argument- based solely on mathematics and the laws of statistics, sums up why I believe evolution is absurd.<br>
<br>
Coppedge, yr. unk.,<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The probability of a single protein molecule being arranged by chance is 10^161, using all atoms on Earth and allowing all the time since the world began… for a minimum set of the required 239 proteins for the smallest theoretical life, the probability is 1 in 10^119,841. It would take 10^119841 years on the average to get a set of such proteins. That is 10^119,831 times the assumed age of the Earth and is a figure with 119,831 zeroes. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
I have lots, lots more if anyone finds problems of holes in these arguments. I didn’t even touch cosmotogolgy… and I’m sure some of my fellows have arguments I’ve never even heard of.<br>
<br>
BTW, MacAlister... pick up the book &quot;The Face&quot; at your local Christian bookstore... maybe those teachers weren't as right as you thought.<br>
<br>
Of course, if you just want to burn it or ignore it like the very sort of person you've been insulting... go for it.<br>
